properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 12 at 7:00PM CST by NWS Green Bay WI
properties.description:
An arctic cold front was plunging southward across northeast
Wisconsin early this evening. The leading edge of the arctic front
extended from south of Wausau to just south of Marinette as of 7
pm. The arctic front should pass through the Fox Valley and the
lake shore region south of Sturgeon Bay by 9 pm. The arctic front
will be noted by a wind shift to the north or northwest with
sustained winds of 20 to 30 mph with gusts to 35 mph, and a
sudden drop in air temperatures.

Light snow continues early this evening across the Fox Valley and
lakeshore region. The snow is expected to linger into early
Thursday morning. Snowfall totals of 1 to 3 inches are expected
by daybreak on Thursday.

The combination of the falling snow, along with melting snow on
pavement surfaces and falling air temperatures well below freezing
could lead to a flash freeze by mid to late evening. Gusty northerly
winds may also create some areas of blowing and drifting snow.

Overnight, temperatures are expected to fall into the single
digits to around 10 above zero. The combination of the cold
temperatures and gusty northerly winds will produce wind chill
readings down to around 10 below zero late tonight into Thursday
morning. Wind chill readings this low can produce frost bite in 30
minutes.

Allow extra travel time if you will be driving this evening as
roads will become slippery due to ice or snow. If venturing
outdoors overnight, wear layers of clothing along with a hat and
gloves to protect yourself from the cold.

NWSheadline: HAZARDOUS TRAVEL CONDITIONS EXPECTED TO DEVELOP THIS EVENING FOLLOWED BY COLD WIND CHILLS OVERNIGHT
